@aquajunkie

Today marks the 10-year anniversary of when this photo was taken. 

Unknowingly at the time, this day would change my life forever. What specifically happened leading up to this moment has been mentioned thousand times over in various magazine captions, online articles, and even in my book. What I find more meaningful is everything that happened after this fateful day. This image now titled “Numb Feet” ended up online for @stab magazine and was my first internationally published work. Little did I know at the time, this would change everything for me. Much more than a minuscule cheque would offer financially, it filled me with confidence and dedication that I didn’t know was possible. Especially after being told countless times that I should stop shooting surfing because there’s no future in it… Fast forward an entire decade and I’m still doing what I love as a career. Better than ever in fact, but still filled with that same passion, inspiration, and creative drive to capture what I see. People often ask what my favourite photo I’ve taken is. Although I don’t think there’s an actual answer for that, this one will always stand out in my heart.

Thank you @petedevries for forgetting your booties.

Life is beautiful.

When I woke up it felt like I was hit by a truck after swimming for 4 hours shooting from the water. Besides the fatigue, I felt so much gratitude. I love surfing, that’s a gimme. I love photography, obviously. Even more than that though, I love all of my friends and surfers in this community. I love the athletes that push their bodies and abilities. I love airs, turns and barrels. I love the Pacific Ocean, no matter how cold. I love Vancouver Island, no matter how fickle. I love my home, my job, my family, my passion, my drive, my strengths, my weakness, my body and my mind. I love this weird life I’ve created for myself. Speaking of which, and most importantly, I love myself.

@reed_platenius for @surfline

Sometimes photos just don’t get published, licensed, or even looked at. And that’s alright, it’s the nature of the business. While it can be disheartening when my work doesn't receive the attention I believe it deserves, it's important to remember that the value of art is completely subjective. Different individuals have different tastes and preferences, and what may go unnoticed by some could deeply resonate with others. To the untrained eye, this specific image probably doesn't hold much significance. Just another underwater pass-by surf shot, right? Well for those who don’t know, this type of water clarity is really rare on Vancouver Island. The water are here never really gets this transparent, let alone when the surf conditions line up properly. I’m so proud of this photo it hurts and it’s a shame that no one besides @petedevries and I have seen it for the last year and a half. So here you go Instagram, it’s on the internet now, free of charge, because if a neat photo never gets seen, does it even exist?

I still had hopes and dreams, but nothing was clear enough for me to focus on. When I got a bit older, I definitely felt lost and was searching something. Thankfully I worked hard and let life unfold as it should. I ended up exactly where I am suppose to be.

We go over the current & ever-changing forecast, wind, and tides of the Pacific Northwest. What we might see, what we hope to see, potential angles to shoot, praying to beat the crowd, and score one of our few fickle waves. We discuss the state of the industry, future shooting opportunities, upcoming swells, sponsor budgets, video projects, creative ideas, etc. Although @petedevries and I have grown from neighbours to colleagues to friends over the years, when we’re documenting surfing, it’s all business.

On the night of January 8th, my dear sweet mother Laura Louise Eaton, peacefully passed away in her sleep after a long battle with breast cancer. Although I don’t typically post things regarding my personal life on social media, it feels essential to honour her beautiful soul publicly. I’m at a loss for words, as it still doesn’t seem real. However, all I can say right now is that I’m the person I am because of her. She’ll continue to live on in spirit through me, as many who know us closely know how similar she and I are. I’m so grateful to have had the opportunity to say everything I’ve wanted to tell her and ask all of the questions I was curious about before she left. Hug the people you care about tightly and love them deeply because you never know when they’ll be taken from us. #FuckCancer
